rows: Quite probably a loan, via English, in a number of languages
Attested as far south as Yugambeh (non-PM)
Elsewhere age- means 'defecate, urinate, eliminate'; poss. here too.
To GYim gaambi. Alternate hyothesis: poss. to Pakanh umpani & UOyk umpa, both black flying fox
Almost certainly freshwater given the location
Phonological development poss. anomalous in KThaypan. Poss. attested as far as Diyari.
UOyk & UOlk alwangar; likely source is UOlkol
Ctenophorus isolepis, Diporiphora spp., Lophognathus spp.
Not south of KThaypan in CYP, but attested in Tangkic; poss. related to *wungul(u)
This is generic for a number of native bee spp and also the English bee
Reflexes of *kañarra on the EAST side of CYP including KThaypan have the 'saltwater' sense; on the WEST side 'freshwater'.
Resembles reflexes of *rirra (tooth) in some languages
Rigsby suggests loan status but does not know source
Attested from northern CYP to Karnic
Doubtful. Resembles a great many 'willie wagtail' words but does not appear to correspond to any. Uolkol ithirrit
